main event: A ground observer and two airborne observers reported seeing an unidentified orange object emitting sparks and descending below the horizon in southwestern Canada on May 25, 1960.
interesting points: The ground observer saw the object flying at a low altitude and emitting sparks, which is not typical behavior for a conventional aircraft.
The airborne observers saw the object directly above their aircraft, which was at an altitude of around 25,000 feet, and the object descended below the horizon.
The object was observed for a considerable length of time, around 15 minutes.
The object was reported to two different military units, the 25th Air Division and the Air Technical Intelligence Center.
The object was initially evaluated as a probable meteor, but the long duration of the sighting and the object's behavior did not align with typical meteor characteristics.
photographs: No photographs included in the report
